segments.text: Recording my experiences down there, you know.
And there's a tremendous change that's come over the college.
Of course, what I think is far different than what most people think.
I think it should never have been changed from a military school.
I think that they infringed on the rights.
It was dedicated as a military, a land-grant college, with the stipulation that military training would be taught
I think it should never have been changed.
I think it should have been limited to a certain number of students.
I think the military standards should have been improved, elevated, and kept strictly as a military school.
Now, that's my opinion.
That's not the opinion of others.
I think it should never become a coeducation.
I think that's wrong.
But that's my opinion.
Well, you're not alone in your opinion.
I don't know what percentage of the people hold that opinion.
Well, a lot of them maybe wouldn't express their opinion about it, see.
But that's what I think about it.
And I'm sorry to see the school has grown too big.
It's gotten entirely too big.
All colleges have, I guess.
Well, a good number of them have.
I don't know if you know what the enrollment is now or not.
It was 18,500.
Yeah.
last fall and expected to go to 21,000 this fall.
Well, of course, that's an enormous enrollment, enormous college.
The state's grown, the country's grown, everything.
But I hate to see a college, a tradition, you know, and like that change over so radically.
But all it is now is just another university.
Yeah.

Well, I've been told by people who were there and were, I guess, involved in the decisions to make it coeducational and non-military was that there was some fear that it would kind of die off if they didn't do something because there were not enough boys who wanted to go to an all-male military school for it to keep going.
Well.
That may be true to a certain extent.
We're softer than we used to be.
That is the people are, the younger generation.
You take the average kid now.
He wouldn't have gone down there and go through A&M when I went through it.
It'd been too rough for him.
He wouldn't have stayed there.
Hell no.
Like a boy from my hometown, he went down there with us.
He stayed.

two days he saw he wanted to see and he went back home to mama decided no place for him and they wasn't well he's better if he decided that he's better off at home than those things but the a and m has turned out a lot of good men oh yeah and those things are what made these good men it's not it's not air conditioning and luxurious dormitories and uh big schools that make good men it's
It's training which makes a good man.
There's nothing better than a good, strong military school for a boy.
Now that's my opinion.
That's the same opinion my dad had.
It might be like you say.
No, they blamed it on the football team.
They said that the reason they didn't have a football team was that they had military training, just like you said.
Then they abandoned that.
Then they blamed the school.
They said they didn't have any girls down there.
They had to get the girls down there so the boys could come to school.
So they got the girls down there.
So then the football team has been going down every year since.
So these athletes
now are so petted and pampered, not from college, but from the cradle right on up.
We've got these little league teams and all that kind of stuff.
And an athlete, unless he's a pretty level-headed sort of a fella, he can't help but be spoiled by the time he gets to college.
And when they get out of college, well, then they either go pro or they coach or something else, you know.
But athletics is not all there is to an institution.
It's good for an institution, but it's greatly overdone.
That's my opinion.
Greatly overdone.
And we used to play for fun.
Now then, they play for money.
Spirit, spirit.
That's what we used to make A&M win football games, the spirit.
Talking about the pampering of athletes and so forth, did the athletes enjoy any particular privileges when you were there?
Well, we were, we were, that is, the athletes were looked up on.
They were, in a sense, sort of idolized, but...
They had privileges.
Yeah, we didn't have to, as I say, we didn't have to attend maybe certain drills and we didn't have to attend retreats and such as that.
We were excused.
But outside from that, why there was no great special privilege for them, no.
Do you have a training table?
Yeah, a training table, yeah.
You mentioned that you played football.
Yeah, I played football.
For how many years?
I was down there.
I was on the team there for a couple of years.
I finally made it in 22.
We had...
We played then for the fun of it, for the spirit.
See, there was a lot of spirit, school spirit.
I take it there were no athletic scholarships when you were there?
No.
We just played it.
And if a fella come in there, a poor boy, and he needed a little help, somebody helped him.
And then he was given a job maybe in the dormitory, maybe...
waiting on tables or something like that or on student labor, but that was taken care of too.
We used to make 20 cents an hour on the student labor.
The fellow wasn't supposed to make over $20 a month.
I mean the student wasn't supposed to make over $20?
He couldn't make over $20 a month.
That was the limit.
I take it you had a job some of the time that you were there.
No, I didn't.
I wasn't on the student label.
You weren't on the student label before?
No, I wasn't on the student label.
The tuition was cheap then.
I used to pay, I think it was $73.50 every semester.
That was room and board and tuition?
Room and board.
We didn't have any tuition.
No tuition.
Room and board, laundry, and...
and you had to have a little spending money.
Well, it didn't take much.
$0.05 or $10 a month would be all right for spending money.
The dollar went a whole hell of a lot farther than that.
It didn't cost much.
I went through A&M for about $2,000.
Amazing.
Not so much at A&M, but there are a lot of schools where they
spend that much in a year.
Some of them spend that much in half a year.
Well, I think there are some schools where the tuition costs you that much.
I think we've mentioned one of the things that made A&M different is the traditions that the students carried on.
Things such as Yale practice, silver taps,
the annual muster, things of that nature, and the bonfire.
Did you have any of these things when you were there as a student?
I'm sure you had yell practice from time to time.
Oh yeah, yell practice if the light was on in the room.
They had Yale practice after supper.
If the light was on the room in the dormitory, they went up there.
Somebody went up there and see why it was on.
Why you wasn't out at Yale practice.
And if it hadn't been a freshman, you got a paddle.
You had to be at that Yale practice.
And you had to attend all the games.
Did you have to attend just the ones in Kiley Station or did you have to go to all the outages?
No, we didn't do that.
They run a special train every year to Cotton Palace in Waco.
We played at Baylor, you know, Cotton Palace.
Run a special train.
The whole Corps went down there and they put on a parade in the morning.
Did you go to Austin too when you played there?
Well, if we could afford it.
But that wasn't a special train then?
No.
You know, that wasn't a special train.
But I don't know who paid for that special train.
We used to meter away a lot of times.
A lot of kids would beat their way, you know, they'd make a freshman buy a ticket.

and then the conductor he'd get he'd have to be on these special planes the conductor just hated those things you know they just give us much trouble and we'd have a sticker a yellow ticket well i just tell anybody i'd have a fish you know
Somebody would have a fish, and they'd say, well, now, if you want to go to this Waco trip here, you buy a ticket.
And then he'd buy a ticket, and then he'd get that yellow slip.
So then he'd work his way up to the front of the train with that yellow slip,
and he'd pass it to me or somebody else, and I'd put it in my hat seat.
So the conductor, he'd come by, and he'd see that yellow slip, and he'd just pass on by.
So then when the conductor got back so far, we have these, you know how these trains connect?
Yeah.
They used to connect.
You could have a passway in there.
Well, underneath was some steps, you know, where you stepped down.
So we just opened those doors and put the freshman under there, or somebody would, and the conductor's never seen him.
He'd just go on by.
So if the conductor, after he went through once, that was enough.
He'd had enough of that.
So then we used to put him on a seat and cover him up with a bunch of overcoats.
We'd cover the upperclassmen up with a bunch of overcoats.
So that's the way we made the trip.
And I went down there once, and I
went free, and then when they got to the Cotton Palace, why, they gave us a dollar.
And that was in trade, see.
That entitled us to buy, and we could take that dollar, that coupon, and cash it in for a dollar on the ground, see, when we got to the Cotton Palace.
So this is the way we used to, and we did this just for fun.
It really wasn't, it was a kind of a game with us.
So that's the way I got by, and then I got mixed up in the crap game coming back on 90 cents out of here.
So I come out all right.
We know that from off and on there were a few girls like faculty, professors' daughters and things like that in school.
Were there any of them there when you were there?
Yeah, there's a girl named Jones.
And you ever heard of Oscar Frazier?
I believe I have.
Well, she married Oscar Frey.
She used to sit right next to me in chem class.
And her father was a chem prop there in organic chemistry.
And there was a rule then that they loosen it up a little.
The professors, if they had a daughter and they lived on the campus, this daughter, they could let this daughter go to school if she wanted to.
And all this liberality started with World War I.
When these veterans returned, we used to have what we called the casuals, casual company.
They were down in Milner Hall after it was vacated by the military.
And they were veterans of World War I.
Somebody got the idea that veterans shouldn't be made to take military training again unless you wanted to.
Now there were some veterans in the Corps too, a lot of veterans in there, but these boys didn't want to take military training.
That's when things really started back then with this casual company.
Then somebody got the idea that A&M students should not be compelled to take military training for their entire school life.
Did they ever start any?

start this the system while you were there whereby you could go to military training two years and be a casual for two no even if you hadn't been in the service that came in later then that was way after i left there oh you you went there you took four years of military training unless you had been a uh all all freshmen were privates uh sophomore where the corporals were picked from the sophomore class
The sergeants were picked from the junior class.
All juniors were sergeants.
They had war stripes.
All seniors were cadet officers.
Before that, way back, they had what they called senior privates.
And they had the old bellhop uniform.
When I was there, every senior was a commissioned officer.
The second lieutenant on it.
So they had no more senior privates when you were there?
No more senior privates.
And every junior was a sergeant of some kind.
And the corporals then were picked from the sophomore class.
But not necessarily every sophomore was a corporal.
No, no, no.
They didn't have too many corporals.
Let's see.
You graduated in the spring of 22.
Did you have a job?
No, I was down there in the SATC.
So we started in, we had a few classes, and then the classes were suspended.
Then they sent me to the hospital.
I worked over in the hospital most of my time down there the first semester.
It was when they had a lot of flu.
That was when they had a lot of flu.
I worked over there in the hospital.
I was an orderly.
They didn't have a medical corps then.
They just picked the details out of a company to go to the hospital.
I guess I did good over there.
They just kept me over there.
Maybe forgot about me.
I don't know.
So then after the thing was over, then they started the next semester after the first year and they gave the
Those that were in the freshman class had a chance to complete their work in five months.
So I got behind.
I didn't complete mine successfully.
I got behind.
I never was much of a student.
Like old Doc Salisbury told me one day, he says, Mr. Lieber, you ought to be out behind the plow.
You haven't got any business in here.
And he is about right.
So he wasn't far at all.
So I busted geology, too.
That's another stiff one for me.
But it's like an old bracket.
He was an English professor, and he said he didn't know which was the smartest.
A man go through college and make all A's and B's, or a man go through college and never crack a book.
So that's the way the thing turned out.
So I was in the...
I finished, left there in February of 1923.
I was there in the fall of 22.
I was behind my class.
Four and a half years.
Yeah, I didn't feel like taking the 23 class because I didn't stay to finish there.
I didn't stay in the spring and so I just took, I think it's three subjects.
in the fall of 22.
I just had three subjects.
Just enough to get my degree.
Okay.
Did you have a job lined up by the time you left school?
No, things were tight then.
They had that panic.
So I thought I wanted to be a county agent.
And I couldn't connect anywhere.
They said they had more county agents than they needed running out there.
So I went to work then for a feed mill, just check aboard feed.
And they were recruiting.
They were after these fellas then, these college boys.
So they were recruiting.
I didn't have any trouble getting a job there with them.
So I carried a grip farm for about 10 years and I quit and went to farming.
And where all did you work for Purina?
I worked about four years in Mississippian and I worked the rest of the year, about six years out here.
So in El Paso?
That's what brought me to El Paso.
I've come out here from the Fort Worth now.
And so what, about 33 or 34, somewhere thereabouts, you quit them and started the farm?
Yeah, I quit.
Well, I had a case of the flu in 32, and I had double pneumonia.
Then a lung specialist told me I had TB, and so I took the cure for about two years, I guess.
So after that, I
at that time do a lot of thinking, so I said, well, hell, I'm going to get out here and farm.
A lot of these, about half these valleys, this valley here, this farm is made up of lungards and chicken people and stuff like that.
There's a lot of veterans out here that have to be beat.
So what kind of farming did you do initially?
I started in cotton farming.
How much acreage did you farm?
oh i found i finally i was broke and i scratched around down here and i finally acquired this property here and it was six acres in it and then i uh

made a little cotton crop and i had a little money and i built the house here i made pretty good wages building the house with myself and a bunch of mexicans i had mexican craftsmen you know helping me i did the carpenter work and so forth and then i uh got the farming out here and i had kind of got my foot in the door and then people there were then at that time were anxious to rent land but all this thing around here was cotton farms now stop there wasn't
There wasn't any houses around here at all.
So they offered me the rent and the land.
I kind of got started that way.
I made a little money, finally.
I finally bought more land, just kept buying land, bit by bit.
Other things happened.
So I sold my land and paid off my debts.
up this place here.
So then I lost some more money in investments.
You can't win all the time.
You roll a dice, you're going to crap out sometimes.
You can't win all the time.
Nothing good ever lasts.
Oh, remember that.
Nothing good ever lasts.
That's one thing you want to remember, young man.
Nothing good ever lasts.
Something will hit you.
You got a good job today, and tomorrow you don't have one.
So be prepared.
So you farmed, what was the highest or greatest acreage you ever had for farming?
Oh, I was a small fry.
I was, oh, I farmed about 100 and 150, maybe 125 acres.
And then I finally acquired 25 acres here in my own right.
I had a nice little farm here, 25 acres, and then I rented land all around, you see.
And just an old sharecropper, you say, you might say.
And then ultimately you sold it all off with the four you have now.
That's right.
Sold it all off to subdivisions, those houses over there.
Used to be my land across the road.
Yeah, got rid of it.
I saw the handwriting on the wall finally.
I quit in 62.
Quit farming.
Quit farming in 62.
And then did you move off the farm?
You moved off the farm for a while.
Well, see, I used to live on the North Loop over here.
I had a nice home over there, and I lived over there.
Like all these plot hoppers do, you know, I had to go to town, so I had to go into town.
Better neighborhood and everything over there, you know.
So I moved over there, and my wife died.
So then we settled the estate, and I come up short, so I can back over there.
I'm just getting by.
I built these little houses and I rent them.
A lot of people think I'm rich, but I'm not.
It's all misleading.
They've just got the idea and can't get it out of their head, but I'm not.
That's why I shouldn't be, but I'm not.
Well, I suppose people that have a posted stamp yard look at you and you've got four acres and they say, my, he must be rich.
Well, they come down here, you know, and they look around and say, God, darn, I wish I had this place.
Nice places.
I just like to have something of this when I retire.
See, I do all this myself.
I'm 75 years old, and I do all this myself every day.
I'm in good health, and that's what keeps me in good health.
Inactivity, cigarettes, and rotten gut booze is killing the young people, even the Mexicans.
In 20 years, if they don't back up and start over, there'll be a hospital on every corner, and they won't be able to take care of them.
The heart attacks, the strokes, the cancers, all that.
That's right.

I see now there's statistics that you were reading yesterday that one in every three families in the United States, they predicted one in every three families in the United States would be hit by cancer.
Astonishing.
Yeah.
And I guess the heart attacks and things like that are getting more and more frequent and younger and younger.
Cigarettes, inactivity, and booze, rock gut booze, this old beer.
These old Mexicans around here, some of them, you just stick a needle in them, the beer just spews.
Big high school kids looked like they had a rubber tube around their waist here, inner tube, see?
No condition whatever, little legs, table legs, big bellies.
Once in a while you see one young Mexican, 23 or 24 years old, have a belly on him like he's 45 or 50.
Yeah.
Go in the pipe, boy.
That's right.
Just think about it.
So what men having 35, 40 years old having heart attacks, 50 years old,
our artifacts.
Not right.
Don't make sense.
What do you produce mostly, or if anything, on your farm now?
Well, I just sowed the whole thing down in Bermuda grass.
And what I've got here, I take a few horses, pasture.
I've got these houses I rent.
I've got a few sheep.
And a few fig trees.
A few fig trees.
And I just sit down here and let the world go by.
And I get to hoeing someday and I think, well, you old fool, what in the hell are you staying out here for?
You ought to be in town making a lot of money.
And then I get to thinking about how I'm going to make that money.
So I say, well, you old fool, you better stay here a while.
At least you got your health.
Good health is the world's greatest blessing.
If you've got good health, you're rich.
You're rich.
There's nothing in the world that can take the place of good health.
I know because I've had mine and I've lost it, and I got it back by mean strength and awkwardness.
But, you know, there's two boys in my football squad down there who died with tuberculosis.
I think both of those boys could have been saved if they'd have been, had the right attitude maybe and they'd have got it in time.
Big fellas too.
Old Spot Hanna, he could kick a football, boy he could place a kick a football 40 yards.
He was a guy who weighed 210 pounds.
He played a guard.
He was really a place kicker.
And Dick Wilson, he was a tackle.
He weighed about 200 and about the same as Old Spock.
And big old raw ball, West Texas boy.
Engineer, got down here in South America or Central America somewhere and started running the temperature and they told him he had tropical fever.
When he finally got back here in the States, he had one of his lungs gone.
That's the way it is.
You never know.
And health is the greatest blessing.
So take care of your health.
